    <h2>What Changed from the Paper SAT</h2>
    <p>The transition from paper to digital was not just a change in delivery method — College Board fundamentally redesigned the test. Understanding these changes is essential for effective preparation.</p>
    <p><strong>Shorter test length:</strong> The digital SAT takes 2 hours and 14 minutes, compared to 3 hours for the paper version (or 3 hours and 15 minutes with the optional essay, which has been eliminated). This reduction in testing time was one of the most requested changes from students and educators.</p>
    <p><strong>Shorter reading passages:</strong> Instead of the long, dense passages of 500 to 750 words that characterized the paper SAT's reading section, the digital SAT uses shorter passages that are typically 25 to 150 words. Each passage is paired with a single question or a small cluster of questions. This eliminates the need to read and retain information from lengthy passages while answering multiple questions about each one.</p>
    <p><strong>Adaptive testing:</strong> The digital SAT uses a multistage adaptive design. Each section — Reading and Writing, and Math — is divided into two modules. The first module contains a mix of easy, medium, and hard questions. Your performance on the first module determines the difficulty level of the second module. Students who perform well on Module 1 receive a harder Module 2 with access to higher score ranges, while students who struggle receive an easier Module 2 with a lower score ceiling.</p>
    <p><strong>Calculator allowed on all math:</strong> The paper SAT had a no-calculator math section and a calculator-permitted math section. The digital SAT allows calculator use on every math question, and a built-in Desmos graphing calculator is available within the testing software. You may also bring your own approved calculator.</p>
    <p><strong>No separate reading and writing sections:</strong> The paper SAT had distinct Reading and Writing and Language sections. The digital SAT combines these into a single Reading and Writing section that tests both skills together through integrated questions about short passages.</p>
    <p><strong>Faster score release:</strong> Paper SAT scores took two to three weeks to arrive. Digital SAT scores are typically available within days, sometimes as few as two to three days after the test date. This faster turnaround helps students make timely decisions about retaking the test or submitting scores to colleges.</p>

    <h2>Digital SAT Section Breakdown and Timing</h2>
    <p>The digital SAT consists of two main sections, each divided into two modules. Understanding the structure and timing of each module is critical for pacing your performance on test day.</p>
